\title{Find Skills}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{Helps users discover and install agent skills when they ask questions like "how do I do X", "find a skill for X", "is there a skill that can...", or express interest in extending capabilities. This skill should be used when the user is looking for functionality that might exist as an installable skill.}

\subtree{
\title{Find Skills}
\p{This skill helps you discover and install skills from the open agent skills ecosystem.}

\subtree{
\title{When to Use This Skill}
\p{Use this skill when the user:}

\ul{
\li{Asks "how do I do X" where X might be a common task with an existing skill}
\li{Says "find a skill for X" or "is there a skill for X"}
\li{Asks "can you do X" where X is a specialized capability}
\li{Expresses interest in extending agent capabilities}
\li{Wants to search for tools, templates, or workflows}
\li{Mentions they wish they had help with a specific domain (design, testing, deployment, etc.)}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{What is the Skills CLI?}
\p{The Skills CLI (\code{\startverb npx skills\stopverb}) is the package manager for the open agent skills ecosystem. Skills are modular packages that extend agent capabilities with specialized knowledge, workflows, and tools.}

\p{\strong{Key commands:}}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb npx skills find [query]\stopverb} - Search for skills interactively or by keyword}
\li{\code{\startverb npx skills add <package>\stopverb} - Install a skill from GitHub or other sources}
\li{\code{\startverb npx skills check\stopverb} - Check for skill updates}
\li{\code{\startverb npx skills update\stopverb} - Update all installed skills}
}

\p{\strong{Browse skills at:} https://skills.sh/}
}

\subtree{
\title{How to Help Users Find Skills}
\subtree{
\title{Step 1: Understand What They Need}
\p{When a user asks for help with something, identify:}

\ol{
\li{The domain (e.g., React, testing, design, deployment)}
\li{The specific task (e.g., writing tests, creating animations, reviewing PRs)}
\li{Whether this is a common enough task that a skill likely exists}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 2: Search for Skills}
\p{Run the find command with a relevant query:}

\pre{\startverb
npx skills find [query]
\stopverb}

\p{For example:}

\ul{
\li{User asks "how do I make my React app faster?" → \code{\startverb npx skills find react performance\stopverb}}
\li{User asks "can you help me with PR reviews?" → \code{\startverb npx skills find pr review\stopverb}}
\li{User asks "I need to create a changelog" → \code{\startverb npx skills find changelog\stopverb}}
}

\p{The command will return results like:}

\pre{\startverb
Install with npx skills add <owner/repo@skill>

vercel-labs/agent-skills@vercel-react-best-practices
└ https://skills.sh/vercel-labs/agent-skills/vercel-react-best-practices
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 3: Present Options to the User}
\p{When you find relevant skills, present them to the user with:}

\ol{
\li{The skill name and what it does}
\li{The install command they can run}
\li{A link to learn more at skills.sh}
}

\p{Example response:}

\pre{\startverb
I found a skill that might help! The "vercel-react-best-practices" skill provides
React and Next.js performance optimization guidelines from Vercel Engineering.

To install it:
npx skills add vercel-labs/agent-skills@vercel-react-best-practices

Learn more: https://skills.sh/vercel-labs/agent-skills/vercel-react-best-practices
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 4: Offer to Install}
\p{If the user wants to proceed, you can install the skill for them:}

\pre{\startverb
npx skills add <owner/repo@skill> -g -y
\stopverb}

\p{The \code{\startverb -g\stopverb} flag installs globally (user-level) and \code{\startverb -y\stopverb} skips confirmation prompts.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Common Skill Categories}
\p{When searching, consider these common categories:}

\pre{\startverb
| Category        | Example Queries                          |
| --------------- | ---------------------------------------- |
| Web Development | react, nextjs, typescript, css, tailwind |
| Testing         | testing, jest, playwright, e2e           |
| DevOps          | deploy, docker, kubernetes, ci-cd        |
| Documentation   | docs, readme, changelog, api-docs        |
| Code Quality    | review, lint, refactor, best-practices   |
| Design          | ui, ux, design-system, accessibility     |
| Productivity    | workflow, automation, git                |
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Tips for Effective Searches}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Use specific keywords}: "react testing" is better than just "testing"}
\li{\strong{Try alternative terms}: If "deploy" doesn't work, try "deployment" or "ci-cd"}
\li{\strong{Check popular sources}: Many skills come from \code{\startverb vercel-labs/agent-skills\stopverb} or \code{\startverb ComposioHQ/awesome-claude-skills\stopverb}}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{When No Skills Are Found}
\p{If no relevant skills exist:}

\ol{
\li{Acknowledge that no existing skill was found}
\li{Offer to help with the task directly using your general capabilities}
\li{Suggest the user could create their own skill with \code{\startverb npx skills init\stopverb}}
}

\p{Example:}

\pre{\startverb
I searched for skills related to "xyz" but didn't find any matches.
I can still help you with this task directly! Would you like me to proceed?

If this is something you do often, you could create your own skill:
npx skills init my-xyz-skill
\stopverb}
}
}